			<title>Authoring Tool Support</title>
			<link>https://legacy.idrc.ocadu.ca/resources/idrc-online/23-conference-slides/214-authoring-tool-support</link>
			<guid isPermaLink="true">https://legacy.idrc.ocadu.ca/resources/idrc-online/23-conference-slides/214-authoring-tool-support</guid>
			<description><![CDATA[<div class="c5">
<h2>"The Best Place to Start to Improve the Web"</h2>
</div>
<div class="c6">
<p>Jutta Treviranus and Laurie Harrison</p>
<p>Adaptive Technology Resource Centre</p>
<p>University of Toronto</p>
</div>
<hr class="c7" />
<p><br /> <br /></p>
<h3>Our Projects:</h3>
<ol>
<li>HoTMetaL 4.0                  	<br /> <br /> Lessons learned from HoTMetaL 4.0:                                         	 
<ul>
<li>Information</li>
<li>Integration</li>
<li>Automation</li>
</ul>
<br /> <br /> </li>
<li>WAI Authoring Tool Guideline Working Group                         
<ul>
<li>Review of existing guidelines</li>
<li>Creation of guidelines for authoring                           tools</li>
<li>Authoring of example help files</li>
<li>Prototyping and specification of                           tools</li>
</ul>
<br /> <br /> </li>
<li>Authoring Tool Evaluation Project                         
<ul>
<li>six courseware products assessed</li>
<li>great variation in features /                           functionality of these products</li>
<li>analysis conducted in terms of student                           user interface</li>
</ul>
<br /> <br />
<h3>Methodology</h3>
<ul>
<li>both accessibility and functionality                           assessed</li>
<li>both designer controlled utilities and inherent coursewareframework features considered</li>
<li>evaluated in terms of integration,                           information, and automation</li>
</ul>
<h3>Accessibility and Functionality</h3>
<ul>
<li>accessibility evaluated in terms of                           conformity to WAI guidelines</li>
<li>priority ranking factored into score</li>
<li>overall functionality evaluated and presented as a ratioto integrated accessibility</li>
</ul>
<h3>Designer Controlled Functions</h3>
<ul>
<li>choice, selection, input utilities                           available to course designer</li>
<li>Example: insert image on home page</li>
</ul>
<h3>Inherent Courseware Features</h3>
<ul>
<li>features and design elements which cannot                           be changed by coursedesiger</li>
<li>Example: navigation system, home page                           layout</li>
</ul>
<h3>Designer Controlled Functions</h3>
<ul>
<li>assessed in terms of integration,                           information and automation</li>
</ul>
<h3>Inherent Courseware Features</h3>
<ul>
<li>inherent courseware features assessed in                           terms of accessibility</li>
</ul>
<h3>Web Course in a Box</h3>
<div>Strengths</div>
<ul>
<li>high functionality-accessibility                           ratio</li>
<li>moderate functionality</li>
<li>includes text links</li>
</ul>
<br />
<div>Weaknesses</div>
<ul>
<li>missing ALT text on icons</li>
<li>help file support is weak</li>
<li>no information provided on                           accessibility</li>
</ul>
<h3>Top Class</h3>
<div>Strengths</div>
<ul>
<li>includes ALT text</li>
<li>ability to turn frames off</li>
<li>moderate functionality</li>
</ul>
<br />
<div>Weaknesses</div>
<ul>
<li>help file support is weak</li>
<li>no information provided on                           accessibility</li>
</ul>
<h3>Knowledge Forum</h3>
<div>Strengths</div>
<ul>
<li>uses text links</li>
<li>high functionality</li>
</ul>
<br />
<div>Weaknesses</div>
<ul>
<li>uses tables to format layout of text</li>
<li>long lists of links</li>
<li>no information provided on accessibility                           in help files</li>
<li>no ALT text (though images not                           critical</li>
</ul>
<h3>Virtual-U</h3>
<div>Strengths</div>
<ul>
<li>ALT text provided on home page</li>
<li>some text links provided for                           navigation</li>
</ul>
<br />
<div>Weaknesses</div>
<ul>
<li>uses frames for all views</li>
<li>uses tables for complex home page                           layout</li>
<li>complex drop-down menus for viewing course                           components</li>
<li>no information provided on accessibility                           in help files</li>
</ul>
<h3>CourseInfo</h3>
<div>Strengths</div>
<ul>
<li>highly functional</li>
</ul>
<br />
<div>Weaknesses</div>
<ul>
<li>no ALT text provided</li>
<li>no alternative text links</li>
<li>extensive use of frames</li>
<li>uses tables to format a columnar layout of                           text</li>
<li>no information provided on accessibility                           in help files</li>
</ul>
<h3>WebCT</h3>
<div>Strengths</div>
<ul>
<li>highly functional in terms of creating a                           broad range of studenttools</li>
<li>"work arounds" are possible to improve                           accessibility</li>
</ul>
<br /> 
<ul>
<li>Weaknesses</li>
<li>no ALT text for images/icons</li>
<li>framed navigation system</li>
<li>framed bulletin board system</li>
<li>java-based tools</li>
<li>no information provided on accessibility                           in help files</li>
</ul>
<br /> <br /> </li>
<li>
<h2>The A-Prompt Project</h2>
<ul>
<li>software module may be integrated into                           HTML editing applications</li>
<li>Windows DLL</li>
<li>may be easily called by programs written                           in C or C++ languages</li>
</ul>
<h3>Three Basic Functions:</h3>
<ul>
<li>HTML element checker</li>
<li>Accessibility utilities (alt text registry, table converter,server-side to client side)</li>
<li>Accessibility user interface model                           including demo dialogs</li>
</ul>
<h3>HTML Element Checker</h3>
<ul>
<li>An HTML editor program can validate HTML                           elements by passingthem to the AVDLL</li>
<li>The AVDLL indicates the accessibility of                           the element</li>
<li>Accessibility problems with an HTML element can be handledby the AVDLL or by the host HTML editor.</li>
</ul>
<h3>About the AVDLL</h3>
<ul>
<li>AVDLL can display its own dialog boxes and                           allow the userto modify the HTML element.</li>
<li>After the element has been edited it will                           be returned tothe HTML editor</li>
<li>The HTML editor may handle user modification of inaccessibleHTML and can use the AVDLL dialogs as a model.</li>
</ul>
<h3>A-Prompt Accessibility Verifier:</h3>
<p><br /> Two Components:</p>
<ul>
<li>File Selector</li>
<li>Accessibility Validator</li>
</ul>
<h3>A-Prompt also includes:</h3>
<ul>
<li>comprehensive set of user-help files on                           the HTML elementchecker</li>
<li>attribute dialog boxes</li>
<li>accessible HTML guidelines</li>
</ul>
<h3>Java Version</h3>
<ul>
<li>developing a freely-distributed Java Bean that applicationdevelopers can easily integrate into Java-based HTML authoring tools.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Accessibility Utilities</h3>
<ul>
<li>alt text registry</li>
<li>table converter</li>
<li>server-side to client side maps</li>
</ul>
<h3>User Interface Model</h3>
<ul>
<li>Interface model</li>
<li>demo dialogs:</li>
</ul>
  </li>
</ol>
